TY  - JOUR
T1  - Non-Manipulable House Allocation With Rent Control
AU  - Andersson, Tommy
AU  - Svensson, Lars-Gunnar
Y1  - 2014/03/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA10893
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 507
EP  - 539
VL  - 82
IS  - 2
KW  - House allocation
KW  - rent control
KW  - rationing
KW  - rationing price equilibrium
KW  - constrained efficiency
KW  - non-manipulability
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA10893
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - In many real-life house allocation problems, rents are bounded from above by price ceilings imposed by a government or a local administration. This is known as rent control. Because some price equilibria may be disqualified given such restrictions, this paper proposes an alternative equilibrium concept, called rationing price equilibrium, tailored to capture the specific features of housing markets with rent control. An allocation rule that always selects a rationing price equilibrium is defined, and it is demonstrated to be constrained efficient and (group) non-manipulable for ?almost all? preference profiles. In its bounding cases, the rule reduces to a number of well-known mechanisms from the matching literature. In this sense, the housing market with rent control investigated in this paper integrates several of the predominant matching models into a more general framework.
ER  - 

