TY  - JOUR
T1  - Macroeconomic Implications of Agglomeration
AU  - Davis, Morris A.
AU  - Fisher, Jonas D. M.
AU  - Whited, Toni M.
Y1  - 2014/03/01
PY  - 2014
DA  - 2014/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA9029
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 731
EP  - 764
VL  - 82
IS  - 2
KW  - Economic growth
KW  - productivity
KW  - increasing returns
KW  - agglomeration
KW  - density
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA9029
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Cities exist because of the productivity gains that arise from clustering production and workers, a process called agglomeration. How important is agglomeration for aggregate growth? This paper constructs a dynamic stochastic general equilibrium model of cities and uses it to estimate the effect of local agglomeration on aggregate growth. We combine aggregate time-series and city-level panel data to estimate the model's parameters via generalized method of moments. The estimates imply a statistically and economically significant impact of local agglomeration on the growth rate of per capita consumption, raising it by about 10%.
ER  - 

